<span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> innovation mechanisms in order to help turn innovation into growth</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> w</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ere</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> therefore</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">pleased to see the government</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">increase their support for the TSB by providing an additional £185m in the spending review.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Despite the positive steps taken by the government in this latest spending review, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">we</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> continue to advocate for a long-term</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and sustained investment in the UK science base and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">remain</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">concerned by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a long-term </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">continu</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ation of the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> spending freeze</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> on the science budget.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">his continued freeze amounts to real-terms cut of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">over </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">10% between 2010 and 201</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">6</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">full impact of this freez</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e has not yet been seen, but is already apparent in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> reduced numbers of grants awarded by research councils – narrowing the research base upon which innovation can prosper – and reduced numbers of PhD </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">places awarded</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> – decreasing the number of ‘coal face’ re</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">searchers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, and those upon whom future innovation will depend</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">UK public spending on R&amp;D has been declining relative to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">its </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">competitors</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> over past decades</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, and now lies at only 0.57% of GDP, noticeably lower than the averages of 0.7% for the EU-27, and 0.8% </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">for the G8 and the OECD.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">4</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The UK is not in a position to be internationally competitive whilst funding </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">R&amp;D at a level significantly </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">below</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> that of its competitors. Long</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-term investment in science is required to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> ensure that the UK is not left behind in th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e global race, and will provide a secure research ecosystem to attract business investment and top-class researchers.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Investment is needed from both public and private sources, but </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">both </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">academic research</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and international comparisons</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> show that these two </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">are complementary and positively correlated.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">RSC </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">urge</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">government </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to introduce </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a long term plan to raise UK science spending to 0.7% of GDP (the current EU average) by the end of the next Parliament in 2020. This would </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">not </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">be an insignificant rise,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> but </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">is achievable, requiring </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a 3% year-on-year increase in spending relative to GDP</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and would be a valuable investment for the long term success of the UK economy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and science base</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Comments on the National Audit Office’s (NAO) review of R&amp;D funding</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> NAO’s review of R&amp;D funding for science and technology in the UK</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(the NAO review) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">is comprehensive</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> provides an informative overview of how science and technology is funded within the UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the origin and value of the various sectors </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">that fund R&amp;D</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the sectors and industries that undertake R&amp;D</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It is concerning to note the high level of dependency of UK private R&amp;D upon just a single sector, pharmaceuticals, and specifically upon just two companies within that sector. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">committee</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> would be well plac</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ed to investigate any barriers to diversifying this research base.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">SMEs are playing an ever increasing role in driving innovation in the UK economy. This is typified by the decline in traditional pharmaceutical company employment, and an increase in small </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and medium biotech companies</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The RSC has long been arguing that investment in science, and R&amp;D in general, will stimulate economic growth. It is therefore noteworthy that “since 2005, other countries’ Higher Education Institutions have increased their sp</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ending on undertaking R&amp;D at a faster rate than the UK [and] could reflect the increasing emphasis that some countries are placing on Higher Education as a way to rebalance their economies and recover from recession”</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In section 4.1 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">of the NAO review, it was noted </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">that the UK is amongst a very small number of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">European Union member states that ha</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ve</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> not adopted national </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">R&amp;D intensity targets and that the EU’s strategy for growth includes a target to invest 3% of GDP in R&amp;D by 2020.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> This</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> should be viewed alongside the recent report produced at BIS, showing the importance of long term targets in convincing global companies to invest in the UK.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">August 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Science Campaign, 2010 </span><a href="http://sciencecampaign.org.uk/?p=2606"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://sciencecampaign.org.uk/?p=2606</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Financial Times, 2010 </span><a href="http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/59dc8108-0c6b-11e0-8408-00144feabdc0.htm"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/59dc8108-0c6b-11e0-8408-00144feabd</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">c0.htm</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.rsc.org/images/campaign_case_studies_tcm18-232087.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">Creating growth by staying ahead in science</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, Royal Society of Chemistry, 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://martin.falk.wifo.ac.at/fileadmin/homepage_falk/files/Falk_2006_RAEF_A_139101.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">Falk, M, Applied Economics</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, 38